      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u help me with this python function? its for my uni tech comp sci lab and the automated grader keeps failing me cuz it says \"time limit exceeded.\" i need to optimize the time complexity so it passes the big test cases (n > 10^7) or i'm gonna lose points. basically just make it fast enough to pass.\n\nhere is the code:\n\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        count = 0\n        for j in range(1, i + 1):\n            if i % j == 0:\n                count += 1\n        results.append(count)\n    return sum(results)\n\nhow do i make this run fast enough so the grader doesn't time out?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The issue with your code is that it has a nested loop, which results in a time complexity of O(n^2). This is too slow for large inputs. \n\nHere's an optimized version with a time complexity of O(n):\n\n```python\ndef solve_problem(n):\n    results = []\n    for i in range(1, n + 1):\n        count = 0\n        sqrt_i = int(i ** 0.5)\n        for j in range(1, sqrt_i + 1):\n            if i % j == 0:\n                if i // j == j:\n                    count += 1\n                else:\n                    count += 2\n        results.append(count)\n    return sum(results)\n```\n\nThis code works by only iterating up to the square root of `i` (since `i` is a perfect square if and only if `i` is divisible by its square root). It also only increments the count by 1 if `i` is a perfect square, and by 2 otherwise. This reduces the number of iterations significantly, especially for larger inputs.",
      "source": "target",
